  <!-- Executive Summary -->
  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>Executive Summary</h2>
    <p style="max-width: 760px;">
      The FDA's Bioresearch Monitoring (BIMO) program has intensified its scrutiny of clinical investigator conduct over the last 24 months.
      Across approximately 5,600 BIMO inspections conducted at US clinical sites between FY2019 and FY2024,
      roughly <strong>1 in 4 sites received actionable findings</strong> — with protocol non-compliance cited in about 60% of warning letters
      issued to investigators, sponsors, and IRBs<sup><a href="#cite-1">1</a></sup>.
      This note extracts three recurring failure patterns at oncology trial sites, each drawn from verified warning letters currently live on FDA.gov:
    </p>
    <ol style="max-width: 760px; line-height: 1.8;">
      <li><strong>Dosing past confirmed disease progression</strong> — the most public 2024–2025 oncology enforcement signal</li>
      <li><strong>Genetic / biomarker sub-study consent failures</strong> — a consent failure mode that appears uniquely in targeted oncology protocols</li>
      <li><strong>Investigational product accountability breakdowns</strong> — protocol misinterpretation leading to unplanned additional dosing in pediatric oncology</li>
    </ol>
    <p style="max-width: 760px;">
      Each concentrates operational risk at the site level, not the sponsor level — meaning most oncology sponsors cannot mitigate the exposure through remote monitoring alone.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Finding 1 -->
  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>Finding 1 — Dosing past confirmed progression (2025 enforcement signal)</h2>
    <p style="max-width: 760px;">
      In September 2025, the FDA issued warning letter <strong>716181-09042025</strong> to Dr. Shirish M. Gadgeel,
      a thoracic oncologist at Henry Ford Health, following an August 5–23, 2024 BIMO inspection<sup><a href="#cite-2">2</a></sup>.
      The central finding: a subject with disease progression per modified RECIST 1.1 —
      initial progression observed on the September 16, 2021 tumor measurement report and
      <em>confirmed</em> on the November 9, 2021 report. The protocol required removal from treatment upon confirmed progression.
    </p>
    <p style="max-width: 760px;">
      Despite that, the subject received IV infusions of the investigational drug on October 12, 2021 and November 9, 2021 —
      with sponsor approval for continued dosing not obtained until <strong>November 23, 2021</strong>,
      <em>after the dosing had already occurred</em>. The subject was not formally removed from study treatment until January 3, 2022,
      more than three months after confirmed progression. The letter cites failure to comply with 21 CFR 312.60.
    </p>
    <p style="max-width: 760px;">
      <strong>Why this compounds in 2025–2026:</strong> as targeted oncology protocols embed hard RECIST-based stopping rules,
      sites running multiple investigational oncology protocols simultaneously must implement per-protocol stop-rule operational
      workflows — not rely on physician memory. FDA's December 2024 draft guidance on Protocol Deviations<sup><a href="#cite-3">3</a></sup>
      signals increased inspection focus on this category in 2026. Sites running more than three concurrent investigational oncology
      protocols should assume baseline exposure unless RECIST-stop workflows are operationalized.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Finding 2 -->
  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>Finding 2 — Genetic / biomarker sub-study consent failures</h2>
    <p style="max-width: 760px;">
      The same Gadgeel warning letter cites a second distinct failure. The IRB-approved protocol required subjects to sign
      a <em>separate special consent</em> for inherited genetic analysis before blood samples could be collected for that purpose.
      No separate consent was obtained for a subject whose blood was drawn for genetic analysis at
      <strong>Cycle 2, Day 1 (May 25, 2021) and Cycle 3, Day 1 (June 15, 2021)</strong><sup><a href="#cite-2">2</a></sup>.
      The letter cites 21 CFR 50.20 — failure to obtain legally effective informed consent.
    </p>
    <p style="max-width: 760px;">
      <strong>Why this is oncology-specific:</strong> targeted oncology protocols increasingly nest optional genetic profiling,
      circulating tumor DNA collection, and biomarker sub-studies inside the main consent. Sites that treat the master consent
      as covering all components face direct 21 CFR 50.20 / 50.25 exposure when a protocol-required separate consent is not obtained.
      The operational risk concentrates at the coordinator level — per-sample consent verification must live in the sample collection workflow, not just at enrollment.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Finding 3 -->
  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>Finding 3 — Investigational product accountability (pediatric oncology)</h2>
    <p style="max-width: 760px;">
      Warning letter <strong>674545-12192023</strong>, issued to Dr. Jeffrey W. Taub
      (Chief, Pediatric Hematology-Oncology, Children's Hospital of Michigan), documents a different failure mode following
      a September–October 2022 BIMO inspection<sup><a href="#cite-4">4</a></sup>. A pediatric subject received
      <strong>three additional five-day cycles of vincristine and dexamethasone at Weeks 53, 57, and 61</strong> —
      beyond the schedule the protocol specified. Root cause: a physician sub-investigator misinterpreted the drug administration schedule.
      FDA specifically noted that pediatric subjects administered vincristine are exposed to serious neurologic and hematologic toxicity,
      amplifying the clinical risk of excess dosing.
    </p>
    <p style="max-width: 760px;">
      The hospital's corrective action plan was found inadequate.
    </p>
    <p style="max-width: 760px;">
      <strong>Why this matters for oncology sites specifically:</strong> protocol schedule misinterpretation is a quiet failure mode —
      it doesn't look like non-compliance until FDA reconstructs the expected vs. actual dosing timeline.
      For oncology protocols with complex dose-escalation, induction-consolidation-maintenance phases, or cycle-based schedules,
      risk concentrates in the handoff between protocol reading and dose administration.
      Sites running cytotoxic or narrow-therapeutic-window oncology regimens should assume this pattern applies unless a formal second-check workflow exists.
    </p>
    <p style="max-width: 760px; font-size: 0.9rem; opacity: 0.85;">
      <em>Note: the Taub letter was issued December 2023 following a 2022 inspection. It remains the most recent public FDA
      warning letter to a confirmed pediatric oncology investigator citing investigational product accountability —
      an enduring pattern, not a stale one.</em>
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Base Rate -->
